SIMPLE: officer
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Officer
<hw>Of"fi*cer</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>officier</ets>. See <er>Office</er>, and cf. <er>Official</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who holds an office; a person
lawfully invested with an office, whether civil, military, or
ecclesiastical; <as>as, a church <ex>officer</ex>; a police
<ex>officer</ex>; a staff <ex>officer</ex>.</as></def> ⟦ldquo⟧I am an
<xex>officer</xex> of state.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(U. S. Mil.)</fld> <def>Specifically, a commissioned
officer, in distinction from a warrant officer or an enlisted
man.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Field officer</b></col>, <col><b>General
officer</b></col></mcol>, <cd>etc. See under <er>Field</er>,
<er>General</er>. etc.</cd> -- <col><b>Officer of the day</b></col>
<fld>(Mil.)</fld>, <cd>the officer who, on a given day, has charge for
that day of the guard, prisoners, and police of the post or camp;
abbreviated <abbr>O. D.</abbr>, <abbr>OD</abbr>, or <abbr>O. O.
D.</abbr></cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Officer of the deck</b></col>,
<it>or</it> <col><b>Officer of the watch</b></col></mcol>
<fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>the officer temporarily in charge on the deck of
a vessel, esp. a war vessel.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Officer</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Officer
<hw>Of"fi*cer</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Officered</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Officering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To furnish with
officers; to appoint officers over.</def>
<rj><au>Marshall.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To command as an officer; <as>as, veterans from old
regiments <ex>officered</ex> the recruits</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Office wire</ent>⟦br⟧
